{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489190"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/613"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.13,0.01,0.13,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/613"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67110"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1221"},{"type":"tags","id":"1767"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42112"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of a facial rash and swelling of his nose. His facial rash preceded the swelling of his nose and worsens with stress and sun exposure. The swelling developed gradually without rapid growth or change. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker with minimal alcohol intake. He practices sun safety with regular sunscreen use and limited outdoor time. He denies any trauma to the area, use of topical treatments, or recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is erythema and thickening of the central face with nodular enlargement of the nose. No lesions are noted elsewhere on his body and there is no palpable lymphadenopathy. He is distressed about the swelling and concerned about cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rosacea","Basal cell carcinoma","Acne","Leishmaniasis","Systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of phymatous rosacea (rhinophyma) along with erythematotelangiectatic rosacea. \u003Cstrong\u003ERosacea\u003C/strong\u003E is a common chronic inflammatory disorder of the pilosebaceous units, typically starting between age 30-60 years. The four main clinical subtypes include erythematotelangiectatic, papulopustular, phymatous and ocular rosacea, though these subtypes are not mutually exclusive. Cutaneous features include frequent or non-transient flushing of the central face, telangiectasia, phymatous changes (skin thickening), and inflammatory papules and pustules. These features can worsen with sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pearly nodule with superficial telangiectasia or as a non-healing ulcer with rolled borders. While this patient has light skin as a risk factor, the absence of ulceration or recent changes makes BCC less likely. However, BCC develops in 3-10% of rhinophyma patients and can hide within the deformed nodular skin, so biopsy may be warranted if suspicion exists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcne\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by open and closed comedones, papules and pustules, commonly occurring in teenagers and young adults. It is differentiated from rosacea by the distribution and presence of comedones. This patient does not fit the typical demographic or display characteristic features of acne.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmaniasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with solitary or multiple reddish macules and papules that quickly increase in size and develop central ulceration. Associated features include flu-like symptoms, weight loss, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, and pancytopenia. The patient has none of these features and no history of travel to endemic areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E predominantly affects women of childbearing age and presents with phases of remission and relapse. While it can cause a malar rash, lupus would not cause skin thickening and nodularity of the nose. Features that differentiate lupus from rosacea include the absence of pustules, absent facial flushing, lack of ocular involvement, and presence of systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rhinophyma is the most prevalent presentation of the phymatous subtype of rosacea and commonly occurs in men over 40 years.","Basal cell carcinoma can develop in 3-10% of rhinophyma patients or easily hide within the nodular skin.","Rosacea is differentiated from acne by the lack of comedones.","Lupus is differentiated from rosacea by the absence of pustules, absence of facial flushing, lack of ocular involvement, and presence of rash involvement of regions other than the face."],"references":["Choi JH, Kim YJ, Kim H, Nam SH, Choi YW. Distribution of basal cell carcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma by facial esthetic unit. Archives of Plastic Surgery. 2013;40(04):387\u201391.","Home - books - NCBI [Internet]. National Center for Biotechnology Information. U.S. National Library of Medicine; [cited 2022Nov11]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557574/","Rhinophyma - StatPearls - NCBI Bookshelf [Internet]. [cited 2022Nov11]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544373/","Walter S, Krueger S, Ho J, Reddy KK. Unilateral rhinophyma: Report of a case and Review. Plastic and Aesthetic Research. 2017;4(3):49."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18208"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18208"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/69dccd62-bc6d-4626-ac55-02182f04414a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/69dccd62-bc6d-4626-ac55-02182f04414a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":435,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67110"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T22:37:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T22:39:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"613"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\u